,800,000 * $35) = **$4,662,981.24**\\n   - **Expected Quarterly Savings**: By deploying the model with the 0.644 threshold, we save **$255,380,454.10** per quarter (over $255M in savings per quarter compared to the baseline!).\\n4. **Daily Flagged Transactions**: At the recommended threshold of 0.644, **1,480.3 alerts** would be flagged daily. This represents an alert rate of 4.76% (241 alerts out of 5,065 transactions in the evaluation set, scaled to a daily transaction volume of 31,111.11). This strictly fits within the team's manual review capacity of 1,500 alerts/day. This represents 98.7% capacity utilization, meaning the current team can manage this volume without needing additional headcount or compromising SLAs.\\n\\nLet's write a python script to generate `/output/recommendation.txt` precisely and neatly.\",\n  \"plan\": \"I will write a python script that writes `/output/recommendation.txt` directly. This keeps the text beautifully formatted and ensures no shell syntax errors occur.\",\n  \"commands\": [\n    {\n      \"keystrokes\": \"cat \u003c\u003c 'EOF' \u003e make_rec.py\\ntext = \\\"\\\"\\\"DEPLOYMENT RECOMMENDATION AND FINANCIAL ANALYSIS\\n===============================================\\n\\nTo: Fraud Operations Team & Quarterly Review Board\\nFrom: Lead AI Audit Assistant\\nDate: 2026-05-27\\nSubject: Deployment Recommendation for XGBoost Fraud Detection Model (v4.2.1)\\n\\nExecutive Recommendation\\n------------------------\\nWe recommend that the XGBoost fraud detection model (v4.2.1) be DEPLOYED with a TUNED classification threshold of 0.644, rather than deployed as-is (with the analyst's default threshold of 0.5) or rejected. This recommendation is based on a rigorous cost-benefit optimization that balances the high cost of undetected fraud against the manual investigation capacity of our fraud operations team.\\n\\nRecommended Classification Threshold\\n------------------------------------\\nWe recommend setting the decision threshold to exactly 0.644. \\n\\nWhy this threshold?\\n- Operational Feasibility: Our manual investigation team of 12 analysts has a hard capacity limit of 1,500 alerts/day. At a threshold of 0.644, the model flags approximately 1,480.3 alerts per day. This represents a 98.7% capacity utilization rate, meaning the team can handle the volume without any additional headcount or backlog buildup.\\n- Cost-Benefit Optimization: Under the constraint that daily alerts must not exceed 1,500, a threshold of 0.644 is the mathematically optimal choice. It minimizes the total quarterly cost to $192.73M. Lower thresholds would generate a volume of alerts that our team cannot review, while higher thresholds would let too many high-loss fraud cases go undetected.\\n\\nExpected Financial Impact (Per Quarter)\\n---------------------------------------\\nBased on Finance-validated cost parameters ($4,200 loss per undetected fraud case, $35 cost per manual investigation) and our quarterly transaction volume of 2,800,000, we have modeled the financial outcomes for different operational scenarios:\\n\\n1. Baseline Scenario: No Model Deployed (Flag Nothing)\\n   - Description: All fraud cases pass through undetected. We incur no manual investigation costs but suffer full fraud losses.\\n   - Fraud Loss: $448,110,562.69\\n   - Investigation Cost: $0.00\\n   - Total Quarterly Cost: $448,110,562.69\\n\\n2. Feasible Deployment Scenario: Tuned Model (Threshold = 0.644)\\n   - Description: The model is deployed with the recommended threshold. Daily alerts are capped within team capacity.\\n   - Fraud Loss (Undetected Fraud): $188,067,127.34  (representing 44,778 undetected fraud cases)\\n   - Investigation Cost: $4,662,981.24  (representing 133,228 investigations)\\n   - Total Quarterly Cost: $192,730,108.59\\n   - Net Quarterly Savings vs. Baseline: $255,380,454.10\\n\\n3. Analyst Draft Scenario: Unfeasible Model (Threshold = 0.5)\\n   - Description: This is the default threshold recommended by the analyst. It is operationally impossible because it flags 4,287.4 alerts per day (285.8% of team capacity).\\n   - Fraud Loss (Undetected Fraud): $113,769,002.96\\n   - Investigation Cost: $13,505,231.98  (assuming all could be investigated)\\n   - Total Quarterly Cost: $127,274,234.95\\n   - Note: Because our team capacity is capped at 1,500 alerts/day, we would actually not be able to achieve these savings. The unreviewed alerts would overflow, leading to unmitigated fraud and a breakdown of fraud operations.\\n\\nDaily Operational Volume and Capacity Fit\\n-----------------------------------------\\nAt the recommended threshold of 0.644:\\n- Daily Transaction Volume: 31,111.11 transactions/day\\n- Daily Flagged Transactions (Alerts): 1,480.3 alerts/day (an alert rate of 4.76% of transactions)\\n- Capacity Capacity Margin: 19.7 alerts/day remaining before reaching the 1,500 limit.\\n- Capacity Status: FITS. No additional hiring or overtime is required. The team will operate at maximum efficiency, blocking a substantial amount of fraud while keeping the workload manageable.\\n\\nStrategic Next Steps\\n--------------------\\n1. Fix Upstream Scoring Pipeline: Prioritize an engineering ticket to investigate why 585 out-of-bounds records (including 500 duplicates) were included in the raw export. Ensure the scoring pipeline does not re-score or append duplicate records in production.\\n2. Implement Dynamic Thresholding: As fraud operations capacity grows (e.g., if we hire more analysts) or if we implement automation tools that lower the cost of investigation below $35, we can lower the threshold (down towards 0.29) to capture more fraud and unlock additional millions of dollars in savings.\\n\\\"\\\"\\\"\\n\\nwith open('/output/recommendation.txt', 'w') as f:\\n    f.write(text)\\nprint(\\\"Saved recommendation.txt successfully!\\\")\\nEOF\\npython3 make_rec.py\\n\",\n      \"duration\": 1.0\n    }\n  ]\n}"
